We recommended the Management to:

Exhaust all efforts to retrieve available documents; 
Improve the filing and maintenance of records and strengthen internal control by requiring proper turn-over of documents by the outgoing employee to the incoming employee;
Coordinate in writing with the Bureau of Treasury on the remittance of the collections for the UPLC (Legal Research Fund) and Building Share and to National Housing Authority for possible reconciliation of records; 
Disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the unaccounted balance of ₱27.123 million for proper information of the users of financial statements.

We recommended that Management:

Adopt policies and internal controls to monitor loan accommodations such that only those employees whose salaries do not fall below the prescribed amount of ₱5,000.00 after deducting the loan amortizations will be accommodated;
Direct those in charge of payroll preparation to exercise diligence in monitoring the monthly net take home pay of officials and employees to comply with the existing law;
Implement remedial measures to rectify the situation of the twenty-two personnel receiving a monthly net take home pay below the prescribed amount; and
Strictly implement the mandatory monthly net take home pay of ₱5,000.00

We recommended that Management: 

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the Journals, DVs and other required reports and supporting documents on a monthly basis without delay in compliance with Item 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular 2009-006;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit the required financial documents and reports not yet submitted for CY 2023 to the Office of the Auditor;
Evaluate and adopt mechanisms that would ensure that all disbursements made by the Agency are properly monitored and completely supported in order to avoid accumulation of unsubmitted DVs; and
If necessary, impose appropriate sanctions to the concerned officers and employees as provided in Sections 122, 127 and 128 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended the Management to:

Through the Municipality to establish an Economic Enterprise Development Office to manage, oversee, improve and expand the Locality’s business ventures; 
Through the Municipality to employ an effective and customized IT system tailored to the LGU’s distinct Economic Enterprises. Until the computerized system becomes available, respective units are advised to maintain financial records for each enterprise separately; 
Through the Accounting unit to maintain separate records and prepare financial statements per economic enterprise in accordance with Section 110 of the NGAS for LGUs and the DBM Manual for financial self-sufficiency review of Local Economic Enterprises; and 
Through the Accounting unit, Engineering office and Treasurer’s office to reassess above approximated Net Income / (Net Loss) of the Economic Enterprises and submit Actual Financial Performance Report per each LGU’s economic venture.

We recommended to the Management to:

Create a special committee tasked to undertake the required physical count of biological assets to establish the actual number and fair value less cost to sell of these biological assets;
Create a special committee tasked to undertake the required physical count of biological assets to establish the actual number and fair value less cost to sell of these biological assets;
Require the General Services Officer/ Municipal Treasurer to Maintain Property Cards for the Breeding Stocks and;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain the Work, Other Animals, and Breeding Stocks Ledger Card (WOABSLC) as provided under Section 114 of NGAS Manual.

We recommended  the Management to:

Through the Municipal Accountant, to demand in writing the immediate liquidation of fund transfer granted to various barangays; 
Through the Municipal Accountant, to verify the absence of any Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) for these projects. If proven to be none, provide a certification signed by both the Municipal Mayor and the Barangay Captain that no MOA was prepared relative to these projects;
To fully adhere with COA Circular 94-013 for future fund transfers to implementing agencies and ensure that MOAs are prepared prescribing the requirements, schedules and basis of accomplishments for project implementation and reporting purposes; 
To assign personnel responsible/ focal person for monitoring compliance with the terms and conditions in the MOA as well as validation of actual accomplishments vis-à-vis purpose for which the fund transfer was granted; 
To assign personnel who will assist Accounting Office to monitor and exhaust possible means to identify the ₱1.78 Million unidentified Due from LGUs; and
Through the Accounting Office to coordinate with the previous accounting-in-charge as to details of these unidentified balances along with the Punong Barangay’s office to verify existence of recorded Due to LGUs.

We recommended and the Management is amenable to:

Ensure that the petty cash fund be stored in a secure location, such as a locked safe or vault, when not in use. The Accountable Officer should only have access to the fund during working hours and should not transport the petty cash outside the office;
Require the accountable officer to maintain a separate cashbook/Petty Cash Register which should be regularly updated and reconciled against the petty cash fund held by the accountable officer to provide a more complete and transparent record of the petty cash fund;
Record adjusting entries to correct the effects of double recording of expenses, copy furnish the audit team; and
Replenishment of the petty cash fund should be requested when the disbursements reach at least 75% of the petty cash, or as the need requires, ensuring that sufficient cash is always available for operational needs.

We recommended and management is amenable to:
Apply the payment of overtime services rendered through Compensatory Time-Off and only resort to overtime pay in exceptional cases;
Formulate and adopt internal rules and procedures on the rendition of overtime services of the employees of the LGU Lagonglong which includes the circumstances on the need to render overtime, the manner of remuneration, and provide copies y of these internal rules and regulations to the DBM and CSC.
Re-locate and/or add biometrics machine in a location where personnel rendering overtime service can safely log in their attendance after the regular office hours, while the use of logbook as supplementary record;
Observe the one-hour break in every 3 hours of continuous overtime service; and
Quantify accomplishments in the reports submitted in relation to the overtime services rendered.

We recommended that Management:

Closely coordinate with the creditor as to the status of the loan account by submitting a written representation and make necessary adjustment entries, if found necessary;
Request for a certification from the loan grantor that the LGU has no outstanding loan as of December 31, 2023 and submit the same to COA.

Create a committee in-charge of back-tracking the documents related to unaccounted costs of PPE;
Conduct physical count of PPE and take note of the items found during the inventory-taking but are not included in the list;
Undertake the procedures indicated in COA Circular No. 2020-006 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account to enable the LGU to come up with reliable PPE account.

